wers, and Moore insists that embracing discomfort is necessary for engaging in open and honest conversations about race. Moore includes a syllabus and other tools for actionable steps that white people can take to move beyond performative justice and toward racial reparations, healing, and reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited StatesvAnecdotes. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacismxHistoryxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 0aWhite peoplexEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aWhitesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ablack history, history, teaching, critical race theory, critical race theory in education, pedagogy, racism, Racial Violence, racial perceptions, racial discrimination, racial privilege, African American history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32485140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324868423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324868/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK